  "answer": "This prior-art assessment addresses your questions on FRB scattering and scintillation analysis based on the current body of literature.\n\n### Co-Detected Two-Frequency Analysis\n\nThere is no published study that performs a systematic, population-level two-screen localization using simultaneously detected, widely separated frequency bands (e.g., CHIME at ~600 MHz and a 1.4 GHz array) to explicitly break the degeneracies between the scattering index $$\\alpha$$ and scintillation bandwidth scaling. While multi-frequency characterizations of individual repeating FRBs like FRB 20201124A and FRB 20190520B exist, they typically treat frequency dependence within single or narrow bands rather than leveraging the wide, multi-instrument lever arm to solve for the screen distance ($$d_l$$).[1][2][3]\n\n**The Gap:** A 12-burst co-detected sample would be highly novel. Current scattering models often assume a nominal $$\\alpha \\approx 4$$ or fit it per-burst with high uncertainty. A joint CHIME/DSA-110 analysis would uniquely enable direct, simultaneous mapping of $$\\tau(\\nu)$$ and $$\\Delta\\nu_d(\\nu)$$ across a factor of $$\\sim 2.5$$ in frequency, allowing you to break the degeneracy between the screen geometry and the spectral index, effectively \"pinning\" the screen position along the line of sight for each burst.\n\n### Population-Level Decomposition\n\nThe prior art centers on the scattering-scintillation consistency relation, $$2\\pi \\tau \\delta\\nu \\approx C_1$$, where $$C_1$$ serves as a geometric factor. Key contributors—including **Cordes, Ocker, Masui, Sammons, Cook, Chawla, and Nimmo**—have established that this relation is critical for distinguishing whether scattering originates in the Milky Way (MW) or the host galaxy/CGM. The population-level approach currently centers on comparing the observed $$\\tau$$ and $$\\delta\\nu$$ against the total DM budget ($$DM_{\\text{MW}} + DM_{\\text{halo}} + DM_{\\text{IGM}} + DM_{\\text{host}}$$).[2][4][5]\n\n**The Gap:** Most studies are currently limited to individual sources or small clusters, treating scattering as an \"excess\" over a Galactic model. There is no population-level, statistical framework that systematically applies the consistency relation across diverse FRB environments to solve for the screen distance as a standard output. Your approach would move the field from \"case studies\" (e.g., \"is this specific FRB's scattering local or host-dominated?\") to a statistical framework that uses screen distance as a primary diagnostic for FRB host environments.\n\n### CHIME and DSA-110 Joint Analysis\n\nPublications on joint CHIME/DSA-110 detections focus primarily on individual interferometric localizations and commissioning milestones. While both instruments are essential pillars of the current FRB landscape, there is no published work describing a dedicated scattering/scintillation study of a multi-burst joint sample.[6][7][8]\n\n**The Gap:** This is a wide-open research space. A sample of 12 co-detected bursts, if analyzed with the proposed joint-fit scattering and scintillation framework, would serve as a \"proof-of-concept\" for the next generation of FRB propagation studies. It would represent the first time a statistical sample has been used to treat the scattering screen not just as a nuisance parameter, but as an observational constraint on the distribution of plasma in the host galaxy and the CGM, effectively bypassing the limitations of single-instrument observations.",
